```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        return false;
    }
    while (n % 3 == 0) {
        n /= 3;
    }
    return n == 1;
}
```

This solution works by repeatedly dividing the number by 3 as long as it is divisible by 3. At each step, we check if the number is still divisible by 3. If it is not, that means we have found the base of the power of three, and we check if it is 1. If it is 1, then the original number was a power of three; otherwise, it was not.

For example, if we call `isPowerOfThree(27)`, the loop will divide 27 by 3 repeatedly until we get 1, and then we will return true. If we call `isPowerOfThree(0)`, the loop will not run, and we will return false. If we call `isPowerOfThree(-1)`, the loop will not run, and we will return false.

Note that this solution has a time complexity of O(log n), where n is the input number. This is because the number of divisions by 3 needed to get to 1 is proportional to the logarithm of the number.

